===Manga===
{{Main|List of Cowboy Bebop chapters}}

Two ''Cowboy Bebop'' manga series have been released, both published by [[Kadokawa Shoten]] and serialized in ''[[Asuka Fantasy DX]]''.<ref name="DX 10/1997">{{cite web|title=ふぁんデラ 1997年10月号・中古・角川書店・通販ショップの駿河屋 |url=http://www.suruga-ya.jp/database/ZNAWO9211.html |publisher=Surugaya Japan |date= |accessdate=May 16, 2014 }}</ref><ref name="DX 11/1998">{{cite web|title=ふぁんデラ 1998年11月号・中古・角川書店・通販ショップの駿河屋 |url=http://www.suruga-ya.jp/database/ZNAWO9221.html |publisher=Surugaya Japan |date= |accessdate=May 16, 2014 }}</ref> The first manga series, titled ''Cowboy Bebop: Shooting Star'' and written and illustrated by Cain Kuga, was serialized from October issue 1997, before the anime series' release, to July issue 1998.<ref name="DX 10/1997"/><ref name="OKWave">{{cite web|title=[Q&A] カウボーイビバップ |url=http://okwave.jp/qa/q261857.html |publisher=OKWave Japan |date=April 30, 2002 |accessdate=May 16, 2014 }}</ref> It was collected into two volumes in 1998, the first one in May and the second one in September.<ref>{{cite web|title=シューティングスタービバップ－カウボーイビバップ－ 1 : 中古 &#124; 久雅カイン |url=http://www.netoff.co.jp/detail/0000025292 |publisher=Net Off Japan |date= |accessdate=May 16, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=シューティングスタービバップ－カウボーイビバップ－ 2 : 中古 &#124; 久雅カイン |url=http://www.netoff.co.jp/detail/0000557001 |publisher=Net Off Japan |date= |accessdate=May 16, 2014 }}</ref> The second manga series, simply titled ''Cowboy Bebop'' and written and illustrated by Yutaka Nanten, was serialized from November issue 1998 to March issue 2000.<ref name="DX 11/1998"/><ref name="OKWave"/> It was collected into three volumes, the first two in April and October 1999 and the third one in April 2000.<ref>{{cite web|title=カウボーイビバップ 第1巻:コミック＆アニメ:南天佑 |url=http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/comic/bk_detail.php?pcd=199999853078 |publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten]] |date= |accessdate=April 25, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=カウボーイビバップ 第2巻:コミック＆アニメ:南天佑 |url=http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/comic/bk_detail.php?pcd=199999853136 |publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten]] |date= |accessdate=April 25, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=カウボーイビバップ 第3巻:コミック＆アニメ:南天佑 |url=http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/comic/bk_detail.php?pcd=199999853185 |publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten]] |date= |accessdate=April 25, 2014 }}</ref> Both manga series were licensed by [[Tokyopop]] for release in North America.<ref>{{cite web|title=February Manga Releases - News |url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2001-12-05/february-manga-releases |publisher=[[Anime News Network]] |date=December 5, 2001 |accessdate=April 25, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=New Manga from TokyoPop - News |url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2003-01-08/new-manga-from-tokyopop |publisher=[[Anime News Network]] |date=January 8, 2003 |accessdate=April 25, 2014 }}</ref>

===Video games===
{{Main|Cowboy Bebop (PlayStation game)|Cowboy Bebop: Tsuioku no Serenade}}

A ''[[Cowboy Bebop (PlayStation game)|Cowboy Bebop]]'' video game, developed and published by Bandai,<ref>{{cite web|title=Cowboy Bebop - PlayStation |url=http://ign.com/games/cowboy-bebop/ps-492285 |publisher=[[IGN]] |date= |accessdate=April 25, 2014 }}</ref> was released in Japan for the [[PlayStation]] on May 14, 1998.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cowboy Bebop International Releases |url=http://www.giantbomb.com/cowboy-bebop/3030-4824/releases/ |publisher=[[Giant Bomb]] |date= |accessdate=April 25, 2014 }}</ref> A [[PlayStation 2]] video game, ''[[Cowboy Bebop: Tsuioku no Serenade]]'', was released in Japan on August 25, 2005,<ref>{{cite web|last=IGN Staff |title=Now Playing in Japan |url=http://ign.com/articles/2005/08/31/now-playing-in-japan-43 |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=August 30, 2005 |accessdate=April 25, 2014 }}</ref> and an English version had been set for release in North America. However, in January 2007, IGN reported that the release had likely been cancelled, speculating that it did not survive Bandai [[Namco]]'s merger to [[Bandai Namco Games]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Hatfield |first=Daemon |title=Missing in Action: The Lost Games of PS2 |url=http://ign.com/articles/2007/02/01/missing-in-action-the-lost-games-of-ps2 |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=January 31, 2007 |accessdate=April 25, 2014 }}</ref>

===Film===
An anime film titled ''[[Cowboy Bebop: The Movie]]'', also known as {{nihongo|''Cowboy Bebop: Knockin' on Heaven's Door''|カウボーイビバップ 天国の扉|Kaubōi Bibappu: Tengoku no Tobira|titled ''Cowboy Bebop: Heaven's Door'' in English}}, was released in Japan in September 2001 and in the United States in 2003.

On July 22, 2008, ''[[If (magazine)|If]]'' published an article on its website regarding a rumor of a live-action ''Cowboy Bebop'' movie in development by [[20th Century Fox]]. Producer [[Erwin Stoff]] said that the film's development was in the early stages, and that they had "just signed it".<ref>[http://www.ifmagazine.com/new.asp?article=6571 IF Magazine: Live-Action 'Cowboy Bebop' Movie Is In The Works] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723215231/http://www.ifmagazine.com/new.asp?article=6571 |date=2008-07-23 }}, IF Magazine.</ref><ref>[http://www.firstshowing.net/2008/07/22/fox-developing-cowboy-bebop-live-action-feature-film/ FirstShowing.Net], Cowboy Bebop Movie</ref> [[Keanu Reeves]] was to play the role of [[Spike Spiegel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2008-12-17/keanu-reeves-hopes-to-star-in-live-action-cowboy-bebop |title=Keanu Reeves Hopes to Star in Live-Action Cowboy Bebop |publisher=Anime News Network |date=2008-12-17 |accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://splashpage.mtv.com/2009/01/16/keanu-reeves-to-play-spike-spiegel-in-live-action-cowboy-bebop-movie/|title=Keanu Reeves To Play Spike Spiegel In Live-Action 'Cowboy Bebop' Movie|author=Elisabeth Rappe|publisher=[[MTV]]|date=2009-01-16|accessdate=2015-12-06}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' confirmed on January 15, 2009 that production company [[Sunrise Animation]] would be "closely involved with the development of the English-language project". The site also confirmed Kenji Uchida, Shinichirō Watanabe and series writer Keiko Nobumoto as associate producers, series producer Masahiko Minami as a production consultant, and [[Peter Craig]] as screenwriter. This was lauded by various sources as a promising move for the potential quality of the film.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117998641.html?categoryid=13&cs=1&query=Cowboy+Bebop|title=Keanu Reeves set for 'Bebop' Actor to star in live-action adaptation of anime|publisher=Variety|date=2009-01-15|accessdate=2009-01-21 | first=Tatiana | last=Siegel}}</ref> At the time it was slated to release in 2011, but problems with the budget delayed its production. The submitted script was sent back for rewrite to reduce the cost and little has been heard about it since an interview with producer Joshua Long on October 15, 2010;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/anncast/2010-10-15 |title=Longview - ANNCast |publisher=Anime News Network |date=2013-09-24 |accessdate=2013-09-28}}</ref> the project currently languishes in [[development hell]]. On May 31, 2013, Watanabe stated that the film is currently "underway" but the "details are a secret."{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} On October 25, 2014, series director Watanabe was asked about the live-action film at the MCM London Comicon. He stated: "I'm afraid I don't know what they're thinking in Hollywood. Apparently the project hasn't come to a stop but I don't know how it's going to progress from here on. I hear that there are a lot of 'Hollywood' problems."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-11-03/cowboy-bebop-director-discusses-proposed-live-action-film-hypothetical-anime-sequel/.80626|title=Shinichiro Watanabe London Comicon|publisher=Anime News Network|accessdate=2015-12-06}}</ref>

===Live action television series===
On June 6, 2017, it was announced that an American live-action adaptation of the series was being developed for television by Tomorrow Studios, a partnership between [[Marty Adelstein]] and Sunrise Inc., which also produced the original anime.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/cowboy-bebop-live-action-tv-series-1202454831/ |title=‘Cowboy Bebop’ Live-Action TV Series in the Works |author=Erin Nyren |publisher=Variety |date=2017-06-06 |accessdate=2017-06-06}}</ref> [[Christopher Yost]] is poised to write the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/06/cowboy-bebop-anime-tv-series-live-action-remake-tomorrow-studios-midnight-radio-chris-yost-1202107884/|title=‘Cowboy Bebop’ Cult Anime TV Series Gets U.S. Live-Action Remake By Tomorrow Studios, Midnight Radio & ‘Thor’ Writer|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=6 June 2017|publisher=}}</ref>

===Other===
An official side story titled ''Cowboy Bebop: UT'' tells the story of Ural and Victoria Terpsichore (V.T. from the episode ''Heavy Metal Queen'') when they were bounty hunters. The story was available in its own official site, however the site was closed and is currently available at the site mirror hosted by jazzmess.com.<ref name=BebopUT>{{cite web | author=Dai Sato | date=2001-04-16 |year= |month= |url=http://www.cowboybebop.org/english/ut/index.html |title=''Cowboy Bebop: UT'' |work=[[Bandai]] |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070705142837/http://www.cowboybebop.org/english/ut/index.html |archivedate=2007-07-05 |accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref>

==Reception==

===Critical reception===
''Cowboy Bebop'' received widespread critical acclaim. [[Anime News Network]]'s Mike Crandol gave the series an 'A+' rating for the dubbed version, and an 'A' rating for the subbed version. He claimed the series was "one of the most popular and respected anime titles in history," before adding that it was "a unique television show which skillfully transcends all kinds of genres." Crandol praised its characters as "some of the most endearing characters to ever grace an anime," and commended the voice acting, especially the "flawless English cast." He also complimented the series' "movie-quality" animation, "sophisticated" writing, and its "incredible" musical score. Crandol hailed ''Cowboy Bebop'' as a "landmark" anime "that will be remembered long after many others have been forgotten", and went on to call it "one of the greatest anime titles ever."<ref name="ANN Cowboy Bebop: The Perfect Sessions Review">{{cite web | url = http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/cowboy-bebop-box-set-dvd | title = Cowboy Bebop: The Perfect Sessions DVD Box Set - Review |date= February 21, 2002 | accessdate = September 8, 2013 | last = Crandol | first = Mike | publisher = [[Anime News Network]] }}</ref> Additionally, Michael Toole of [[Anime News Network]] named ''Cowboy Bebop'' as one of the most important anime of the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Toole|first1=Mike|title=Evangel-a-like - The Mike Toole Show|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/the-mike-toole-show/2011-06-05|website=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=20 November 2015|date=5 June 2011}}</ref>

T.H.E.M. Anime Reviews gave the entire series a perfect score of 5 out of 5 stars, with reviewer Christina Carpenter believing ''Cowboy Bebop'' as "one of the best [anime]" and touting it as a masterpiece that "puts most anime...and [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]], to shame." She described it as a "very stylish, beautifully crafted series that deserves much more attention than it gets." Carpenter praised the animation as "a rarity and a marvel to behold" and that it was "beyond superb," and the plot and characterization as having "a sophistication and subtlety that is practically one-of-a-kind." She also praised the soundtrack, and hailed the opening theme as one of the best intro pieces she had ever heard. Carpenter went to say that ''Bebop'' was a "must-have for any serious collector of Japanese animation."<ref name="THEM Cowboy Bebop Review">{{cite web | url = http://www.themanime.org/viewreview.php?id=413 | title = Cowboy Bebop Review |date= | accessdate = September 8, 2013 | last = Carpenter | first = Christina | publisher = T.H.E.M. Anime Reviews }}</ref>

In his article "Asteroid Blues: The Lasting Legacy of Cowboy Bebop", ''[[The Atlantic]]'' writer Alex Suskind states, "On paper, ''Cowboy Bebop'', the legendary cult anime series from Shinichirō Watanabe, reads like something John Wayne, Elmore Leonard, and Philip K. Dick came up with during a wild, all-night whiskey bender." He goes on to write, "The response from critics and fans may have sounded hyperbolic—the word 'masterpiece' was thrown around a great deal—but the praise was justified. First-time solo director Watanabe had created a gorgeous tale of morality, romance, and violence–a dark look at the lives of outlaws that's shot like an independent film."<ref name=atlantic>{{cite web | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/12/asteroid-blues-the-lasting-legacy-of-cowboy-bebop/383817/ | title=Asteroid Blues: The Lasting Legacy of Cowboy Bebop | author=Suskind, Alex | date=December 17, 2014 | work=[[The Atlantic]] | publisher=[[Atlantic Media]] | accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref>

In January 2015, television writer Kyle Mills of [[DVD Talk]] awarded the series five stars upon review. He stated, "Regardless of the medium, be it live action television, film, or animation, ''Cowboy Bebop'' is simply one of the finest examples of storytelling ever created." In his review, he describes the finale as "one of the best in television history," referring to it as a "widely revered" ending that "still sparks fan conversation, resonating with viewers 15 years on." He closes by writing, "''Cowboy Bebop'' ends with a bang."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/65491/cowboy-bebop-the-complete-series-premium-edition-amazon-exclusive/|title=Cowboy Bebop: The Complete Series (Blu-ray)|website=DVD Talk}}</ref>

The series holds a 100% approval rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], with the site’s critical consensus stating, “Blending a head-spinning array of genres and references, Cowboy Bebop is an anime television classic that must be experienced.”<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/cowboy_bebop/s01|title=Cowboy Bebop: Series 1 - Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=}}</ref>

===Accolades===
In the 1999 [[Anime Grand Prix]] awards for the anime of 1998, ''Cowboy Bebop'' won two 1st place awards: Spike Spiegel was awarded the [[Animage#Character|best male character]]; and [[Megumi Hayashibara]] was awarded the [[Animage#Voice acting|best voice actor]] for her role as Faye Valentine. ''Cowboy Bebop'' also received rankings in other categories: the series itself was awarded the 2nd [[Animage#Title|best anime series]]; Faye Valentine and Ed were ranked the 5th and 9th [[Animage#Character|best female characters]] respectively; "Tank!" and "The Real Folk Blues" were ranked the 3rd and 15th [[Animage#Song|best songs]] respectively; and "[[List of Cowboy Bebop episodes#ep5|Ballad of Fallen Angels]]", "[[List of Cowboy Bebop episodes#ep18|Speak Like a Child]]", "[[List of Cowboy Bebop episodes#ep9|Jamming with Edward]]" and "[[List of Cowboy Bebop episodes#epXX|Mish-Mash Blues]]" were ranked the 2nd, 8th, 18th and 20th [[Animage#Episode|best episodes]] respectively.<ref name="AGP 1999">{{cite web|url=http://animage.jp/old/gp/gp_1999.html |title=21st Anime Grand Prix |date=June 1999 |accessdate=September 8, 2013 |publisher=''[[Animage]]'' |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101112183628/http://animage.jp/old/gp/gp_1999.html |archivedate=November 12, 2010 }}</ref>

In the 2000 Anime Grand Prix awards for the anime of 1999, ''Cowboy Bebop'' won the same two 1st place awards again: best male character for Spike Spiegel; and best voice actor for Megumi Hayashibara. Other rankings the series received are: 2nd best anime series; 6th best female character for Faye Valentine; 7th and 12th best song for "Tank!" and "Blue" respectively; and 3rd and 17th best episode for "[[List of Cowboy Bebop episodes#ep26|The Real Folk Blues (Part 2)]]" and "[[List of Cowboy Bebop episodes#ep24|Hard Luck Woman]]" respectively.<ref name="AGP 2000">{{cite web|url=http://animage.jp/old/gp/gp_2000.html |title=22nd Anime Grand Prix |date=June 2000 |accessdate=September 10, 2013 |publisher=''Animage'' |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150410004053/http://animage.jp/old/gp/gp_2000.html |archivedate=April 10, 2015 }}</ref> In the 2000 [[Seiun Award]]s, Cowboy Bebop was awarded for [[Seiun Award#Best Media of the Year|Best Media of the Year]].<ref name="SF Award">{{cite web|url=http://www.sf-fan.gr.jp/awards/list.html |title=List of Seiun Award Winners |date=April 24, 2011 |accessdate=September 8, 2013 |publisher=Federation of the Science Fiction Fan Groups of Japan |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101013043459/http://www.sf-fan.gr.jp/awards/list.html |archivedate=October 13, 2010 }}</ref>

A 2004 poll in ''Newtype USA'', the US edition of the Japanese magazine ''[[Newtype]]'', asked its readers to vote the "Top 25 Anime Titles of All Time"; ''Cowboy Bebop'' ranked 2nd on the list (after ''[[Neon Genesis Evangelion (anime)|Neon Genesis Evangelion]]''), placing it as one of the most socially relevant and influential anime series ever created.<ref>{{cite web|title= Newtype USA Announces the Top 25 Anime of All Time|url= http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/pressrelease.php?id=632 |publisher=Anime News Network |date= October 13, 2006 |accessdate= September 10, 2007 }}</ref> During that same year, ''[[Cinefantastique]]'' listed the anime as one of the "10 Essential Animations", citing the series' "gleeful mix of noir-style, culture-hopping inclusiveness and music".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Persons|first1=Dan|title=The Americanization of Anime: 10 Essential Animations|journal=[[Cinefantastique]]|date=February–March 2004|volume=36|issue=1|page=48|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ly0nAQAAIAAJ&dq=editions:0AFLRE736LO1AnqYXhN92VLUi3o6sFT1GgYU-Fw2cLmjwIZk1c7q9_ZE|accessdate=April 28, 2017}}</ref> In 2007, the American Anime magazine ''[[Anime Insider]]'' listed the "50 Best Anime Ever" by compiling lists of industry regulars and magazine staff, and ranked ''Cowboy Bebop'' as the #1 anime of all time.<ref>{{cite journal |journal=[[Anime Insider]]|issue=50-52|date=November 2007|publisher=[[Wizard Entertainment]]|title=Best Anime Ever}}</ref> In 2012, [[Madman Entertainment]] compiled the votes of fans online for "The Top 20 Madman Anime Titles" and ranked ''Cowboy Bebop'' at #7.<ref name="Madman Top 20">{{cite web | url = http://www.madman.com.au/top20/countdown/7 | title = The Top 20 Madman Anime Titles - 2012. |year = 2012 | accessdate = September 8, 2013 | publisher = [[Madman Entertainment]] }}</ref>

''Cowboy Bebop'' has been featured in several lists published by [[IGN]]. In the 2009 "Top 100 Animated TV Series" list, ''Cowboy Bebop'', labelled as "a very original -- and arguably one of the best -- anime", was placed 14th, making it the second highest ranking anime on the list (after ''Evangelion'') and one of the most influential series of the 1990s.<ref name="IGN 100 TV">{{cite web | url = http://tv.ign.com/top-100-animated-tv-series/14.html | title = Top 100 Animated TV Series - 14. Cowboy Bebop | date = January 14, 2009 | accessdate = December 27, 2012 | publisher = IGN | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121001012745/http://tv.ign.com/top-100-animated-tv-series/14.html | archivedate = October 1, 2012 | df =  }}</ref> In 2011, ''Bebop'' was ranked 29th in the "Top 50 Sci-Fi TV Shows" list, once again being the second highest ranking anime on the list (after ''Evangelion'').<ref name="IGN 50 Sci-Fi">{{cite web | url = http://ign.com/articles/2011/02/21/top-50-sci-fi-tv-shows?page=3 | title = Top 50 Sci-Fi TV Shows |date = February 21, 2011 | accessdate = September 8, 2013 | last1 = Pirello | first1 = Phil | last2 = Collura | first2 = Scott | last3 = Vejvoda | first3 = Jim | last4 = Schedeen | first4 = Jesse | last5 = Goldman | first5 = Eric | last6 = Fowler | first6 = Matt | publisher = IGN }}</ref> In 2006, ''Cowboy Bebop''{{'}}s soundtrack was ranked #1 in "Top Ten Anime Themes and Soundtracks of All-Time" list, with the series being commented as "one of the best anime ever and certainly is tops when it comes to music."<ref name="IGN 10 Anime Soundtracks">{{cite web | url = http://music.ign.com/articles/708/708910p2.html | title = Ten Anime Themes and Soundtracks of All-Time | date = May 16, 2006 | accessdate = September 8, 2013 | last = Pool | first = Josh | publisher = IGN | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120307054225/http://music.ign.com/articles/708/708910p2.html | archivedate = March 7, 2012 | df =  }}</ref> Spike Spiegel was ranked 4th place in the "Top 25 Anime Characters of All Time" article.<ref name="IGN 25 Anime Characters">{{cite web | url = http://ign.com/articles/2009/10/21/top-25-anime-characters-of-all-time?page=5 | title = Top 25 Anime Characters of All Time  |date = October 20, 2009 | accessdate = September 8, 2013 | last = Mackenzie | first = Chris | publisher = IGN }}</ref> IGN Movies also placed ''Cowboy Bebop'' in their list of "10 Cartoon Adaptations We'd Like to See".<ref name="IGN Cartoon Adaptations">{{cite web | url = http://ign.com/articles/2009/08/07/10-cartoon-adaptations-wed-like-to-see?page=2 | title = 10 Cartoon Adaptations We'd Like to See  |date = August 7, 2009 | accessdate = September 8, 2013 | last = IGN Movies | publisher = IGN }}</ref>

[[WatchMojo.com]] has also placed ''Cowboy Bebop'' on multiple ranking lists.  In 2013,  the show ranked #6 on their "Top 10 Anime Series" list.<ref name="WatchMojo">{{cite web |url=http://watchmojo.com/video/id/11928/ |title=WatchMojo.com: Top 10 Anime Series |publisher=[[WatchMojo.com]] |date=October 16, 2013 |accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>  They also ranked the character of Vicious as #6 on their "Top 10 Anime Villains".<ref name="WatchMojo 2">{{cite web |url=http://watchmojo.com/video/id/11848/ |title=WatchMojo.com: Top 10 Anime Villains |publisher=[[WatchMojo.com]] |date=September 12, 2013 |accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref> In 2014 respectively, the company also ranked the show's opening theme sequence as #9 on their "Top 10 Anime Opening Theme Songs"<ref name="WatchMojo 3">{{cite web |url=http://watchmojo.com/video/id/12443/ |title=WatchMojo.com: Top 10 Anime Opening Themes |publisher=[[WatchMojo.com]] |date=May 3, 2014 |accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref> and gave Spike Speigel an honorable mention in their "Top 10 Anime Anti-Heroes" list.<ref name="WatchMojo 4">{{cite web |url=http://watchmojo.com/video/id/12254/ |title=WatchMojo.com: Top 10 Anime Anti-Heroes |publisher=[[WatchMojo.com]] |date=May 17, 2014 |accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>  On a revised 2017 listing for Top 10 Anime Series of All Time, the show was ranked at #2.<ref name="WatchMojo 5">{{cite web |url=https://www.watchmojo.com/video/id/18374/ |title=WatchMojo.com: Top 10 Anime Series of All Time |publisher=[[WatchMojo.com]] |date=March 26, 2017 |accessdate=May 5, 2018}}</ref>

===Analysis===
The series has been subject to study and analysis since its debut, with the main focus being on its style and mixture of genres. Miguel Douglas, describing the series style in a review, said that "the series distinctly establishes itself outside the realm of conventional [[Anime|Japanese animation]] and instead chooses to forge its own path. With a setting within the realm of [[science fiction]], the series wisely offers a world that seems entirely realistic considering our present time. Free from many of the elements that accompany science fiction in general — whether that be [[Extraterrestrial life|space aliens]], giant [[robot]]s, or [[laser gun]]s — the series delegates itself towards presenting a world that is quite similar to our own albeit showcasing some technological advances. Certainly not as pristine a future we would see in other series or films, ''Cowboy Bebop'' decides to deliver a future that closely reflects that of our own time. This aspect of familiarity does wonders in terms of relating to the viewer, and it presents a world that certainly resembles our very own."<ref name="iSreview">{{cite web|title=Anime Review: Cowboy Bebop - カウボーイビバップ - Kaubōi Bibappu|date=September 1, 2010|last=Douglas|first=Miguel|publisher=iSugoi|url=http://www.isugoi.com/cowboy-bebop-review/|accessdate=May 15, 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111113081241/http://www.isugoi.com/cowboy-bebop-review/|archivedate=November 13, 2011|df=}}</ref> Daryl Surat of ''[[Otaku USA]]'', commenting on the series' appeal, said that it was "that rare breed of science-fiction: "accessible". Unlike many anime titles, viewers weren't expected to have knowledge of [[Culture of Asia|Asian culture]] — character names, signs, and the like were primarily in English to begin with — or have seen any other anime series prior."<ref name="ReflectBebop">{{cite web|title=Cowboy Bebop: Reflections on a Modern-Day Anime Relic|date=December 16, 2010|last=Surat|first=Daryl|publisher=[[Otaku USA]]|url=http://www.otakuusamagazine.com/SearchAudience/News1/Cowboy_Bebop_3984.aspx|accessdate=May 13, 2012}}</ref> Michelle Onley Pirkle, in her book ''Science Fiction Film, Television, and Adaptation: Across the Screens'', said that "[''Cowboy Bebop''] is taking a new take on genre, not by creating unique images and sounds, but by playing "freely" with, "remixing", or adapting the images and sounds of other familiar genres in a dynamic way."<ref name="SFbebop">{{cite book|author=Pirkle, Michelle Onley|editor=Jay Telotte|editor2=Gerald Duchovnay|title=Science Fiction Film, Television, and Adaptation: Across the Screens|publisher=[[Routledge]]|date=2011|isbn=978-1-136-65009-3|chapter=Déjà Vu All Over Again?: Cowboy Bebop's Transformation to the Big Screen}}</ref>{{Rp|164}} Robert Baigent, writing for the ''Graduate Journal of Asia-Pacific Studies'', said that the series' appeal likely stemmed from the trend in anime to emulate Western fiction.<ref name="BAIGENT"/>

==Legacy==
In March 2009, the print and web editions of [[The Onion]]'s ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' called ''Cowboy Bebop'' "rightly a huge hit", and listed it as a gateway series to understanding the medium of anime as a whole.<ref name="avclub-2009"/> Suskind said: "It was unlike anything the genre had seen before. It even approached its music differently. The show kicked off with a wormhole of a theme song, and the soundtrack moves so seamlessly through genres, from rock to country to pop to jazz to funk, it's shocking to learn that one set of musicians is behind it all". In an interview, producer Sean Akins also states that the series "created a whole new world". "It's hard for me to quantify the impact that I think it has had. It changed anime. I think people began to think about what shows would be cool. I think it redefined cool within animation, not only in Japan but in the States".<ref name=atlantic/>

American film director, screenwriter, and producer [[Rian Johnson]] has cited ''Cowboy Bebop'' as a visual influence on his films, most notably ''[[Brick (film)|Brick]]''.<ref name="visuals">{{cite web
| url = http://www.rcjohnso.com/forum/viewtopic.php?p=2350&sid=587c10758d5009ad4225fcaa91ef524b#p2350
| title = The Visuals of Brick
| first = Rian |last=Johnson
| work = Rian's Forum
| publisher=rcjohnso.com
| date = April 19, 2006
| accessdate = 2007-03-09
}}</ref> ''[[Ender's Game]]'' writer, novelist, critic, playwright, and poet [[Orson Scott Card]] also praised the series. He states that the series is "better than most sci-fi films out there". He goes on to say that he "found this series brilliant, but what held me was a combination of strong relationship-based storytelling, a moody visual style that never got old and really smart dialogue".<ref name=atlantic/>

After the creation of the series, an interviewer asked Watanabe if he had any plans to create more ''Cowboy Bebop'' material. Watanabe responded by saying that he does not believe that he "should just keep on making ''Cowboy Bebop'' sequels for the sake of it". Watanabe added that ending production and "to quit while we're ahead when people still want more" is more "in keeping with the ''Bebop'' spirit".<ref name="WatanabeInterviewCBMovie">"[https://web.archive.org/web/20030307023145/http://www.cowboybebop.org/english/door/interview/index.html The Director's Voice Shinichiro Watanabe Interview]." ''CowboyBebop.com''.</ref> In a more recent interview from 2006 with ''[[The Daily Texan]]'', Watanabe was asked if there would ever be more ''Cowboy Bebop''. Watanabe's answer was "someday...maybe, someday".<ref>{{cite news | last = Leathers  | first = Kevin | title = Classics of Anime – Cowboy Bebop | work = [[Anime Network#Anime Network (UK)|UK Anime Network]] | page = 2 | language = | publisher = | date = 2009-06-10 | url = http://www.uk-anime.net/articles/Classics_of_Anime_-_Cowboy_Bebop/2 | accessdate = May 2, 2012}}</ref>

